#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid "Guardrails with OPA Policies in Quarkus LangChain4j"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: synopsis
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid "Implementing input guardrails with Open Policy Agent (OPA) for secure LLM applications."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid "As LLMs become integral to enterprise applications, securing the prompts they receive is critical."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid ""
"https://docs.quarkiverse.io/quarkus-langchain4j/dev/index.html[Quarkus LangChain4j] is a Quarkus extension that allows\n"
"users to integrate AI into applications, and the\n"
"https://quarkus.io/quarkus-workshop-langchain4j/[Quarkus LangChain4j Workshop] is a good way to learn about and practice\n"
"the fundamentals."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid ""
"Regarding security, https://quarkus.io/quarkus-workshop-langchain4j/section-1/step-09[Step 9] describes _input\n"
"guardrails_, showcasing an example of how a separate LLM can be used to detect _prompt injection_ attacks.\n"
"However, this approach has costs, both in terms of tokens and performance."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid ""
"Deterministic pattern matching can catch obvious attacks faster, and delegating to the LLM becomes the last option,\n"
"thus reducing the aforementioned effects."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid ""
"At the same time, https://www.openpolicyagent.org/[Open Policy Agent] can be used to define declarative policies\n"
"that can be externalized."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid "This post shows how to combine both approaches in Quarkus LangChain4j."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid "Open Policy Agent (OPA)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid "Pattern matching against a regex is straightforward, but the usual limitations apply:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid "rules are subject to change"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid "rules are usually defined by someone who is not strictly an application developer"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid "rules should be defined independently of the application lifecycle."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid ""
"This is where https://www.openpolicyagent.org/[Open Policy Agent] comes to help.\n"
"It provides a framework that streamlines policy management across application deployment technologies, resources and\n"
"roles."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid ""
"In our specific use case, deterministic guardrails can be defined as OPA policies, decoupling them from the application\n"
"logic, e.g.:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid ""
"The above https://www.openpolicyagent.org/docs/latest/policy-language/[Rego] snippet defines an OPA policy that parses\n"
"the prompt to find either exact or regex matches of malicious content."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid ""
"Deterministic input guardrails could use such policy to detect a prompt injection attack, and the policy can be\n"
"updated by the security team, independently of the application business logic and lifecycle."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid "Now, how to quickly integrate OPA policy evaluation into our example Java application?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid "Adding Wasm to the recipe"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid ""
"Several source languages can be compiled to Wasm, and WebAssembly runtimes exist that allow integrating Wasm modules\n"
"into applications."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid ""
"By adding https://github.com/StyraOSS/opa-java-wasm[Styra Open Policy Agent WebAssembly Java SDK] to the recipe, we\n"
"can obtain an application that is capable of fast and in-process OPA policy evaluation, e.g.:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid ""
"The OPA-based guardrail scans the prompt deterministically, but how can it fall back to the LLM when the pattern match\n"
"is inconclusive?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid "The answer lies in https://www.openpolicyagent.org/docs/latest/extensions/[OPA extensions], which the https://github.com/StyraOSS/opa-java-wasm[Styra SDK] implements as custom builtins."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid ""
"Let's add a set of suspicious words to the Rego policy definition, in order to catch weak signals of a prompt injection\n"
"attack, and the logic to delegate to the LLM evaluation in such a case:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid ""
"The above Rego code snippet defines the logic to call a _builtin_ function, i.e. `llm_score`, when the\n"
"deterministic evaluation returns a score that is under the value signaling a potential prompt injection attack."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid ""
"The `llm_score` function must be declared in a `capabilities.json` file that will be used when compiling Rego into\n"
"Wasm, for the OPA compiler to accept it:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid "The guardrail is the WebAssembly policy: when it needs deeper analysis, it calls the LLM as a custom builtin:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-07-10-quarkus-langchain4j-opa-guardrails.adoc
msgid ""
"User Input\n"
"    │\n"
"    ▼\n"
"┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n"
"│            OPA Wasm Policy (342 KB)                 │\n"
"│                                                     │\n"
"│  1. Pattern matching                                │\n"
"│     ├─ score > 0.7  ──►  BLOCKED     (< 1ms, $0)    │\n"
"│     ├─ score = 0.0  ──►  ALLOWED     (< 1ms, $0)    │\n"
"│     └─ 0 < score ≤ 0.7                              │\n"
"│          │                                          │\n"
"│  2.      └─► llm_score() custom builtin             │\n"
"│               │    OPA calls the LLM as a           │\n"
"│               │    data source, not a guardrail     │\n"
"│               ▼                                     │\n"
"│          OPA makes the final decision               │\n"
"└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n"
"    │\n"
"    ▼\n"
"  CustomerSupportAgent (Quarkus + LangChain4j AI Service)"
msgstr ""

